    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-02-21T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-02-21T19:00:00-05:00" n="169"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d169">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">340.290/2–2151: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Consulate General at Lahore</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-02-21T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 21, 1951—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>64. For Gay. <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss> is making highest level
                    approach Brit <gloss target="#t_FonOff1">FonOff</gloss> re Chi representation
                        <gloss target="#t_ECAFE1">ECAFE</gloss>. We are requesting that <gloss
                        target="#t_UKDel1">UKDel</gloss> be given latitude work out with <gloss
                        target="#t_USDel1">USDel</gloss> some procedural arrangement to avoid vote
                    on substance issue which both Dels cld support or on which UK cld at least
                    abstain. Will inform you soonest results this approach.</p>
                <p>If <gloss target="#t_UKDel1">UKDel</gloss> given discretion most feasible
                    arrangement may be for you get UKRep agree abstain on resolution similar to Thai
                    res last year. UK cld explain vote on ground it consistent with UK abstention
                    same res last year.</p>
                <p>Forurinfo <gloss target="#t_UKDel1">UKDel</gloss> NY voted in favor US
                    postponement motion in Jt Comite to coordinate work <gloss target="#t_AECCCA1"
                        >AEC–CCA</gloss> and explained vote on ground that irrespective of effect
                        <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> res Dec 14 Comite was not competent decide
                    representation question. Prior to Comite meeting Laskey<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d169fn1">Denis S. Laskey, First Secretary, Permanent Delegation of
                        the United Kingdom to the United Nations.</note> told <gloss
                        target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> that his instructions wld permit him support
                    move postpone Chi representation issue but UK was not to identify itself with
                    position that <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> res Dec 14 was proper basis for
                    postponement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
